<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading eplus-wrapper" id=3D"6-long-division-method">=
Long Division Method</h2>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">The best way to find the remainder is the <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.splashlearn.com/math-vocabulary/division/long-division">lo=
ng division</a> method. When the dividend is a large number, it is better t=
o use the long division method. It is a method for dividing large numbers i=
nto smaller groups or parts. It helps to break down a problem into simple a=
nd easy steps.</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Note that the remainder always has to be less th=
an the divisor. If it is more than the divisor, it means the long division =
is incomplete.</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Example: Divide 75 by 4. Find the remainder.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full eplus-wrapper"><img decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"620" height=3D"376" src=3D"https://www.splashlearn.com/math-=
vocabulary/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/What-is-Remainder-3.png" alt=3D"findi=
ng remainder using long division" class=3D"wp-image-27423" title=3D"finding=
 remainder using long division"></figure>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading eplus-wrapper" id=3D"7-properties-of-a-remain=
der">Properties of a Remainder</h2>



<ul class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-list">
<li class=3D"eplus-wrapper">A remainder is always less than the divisor.&nb=
sp;</li>



<li class=3D"eplus-wrapper">If one number (divisor) divides the other numbe=
r (dividend) completely, then the remainder is 0. It is referred to as a co=
mplete division.</li>



<li class=3D"eplus-wrapper">If a dividend is a multiple of the divisor, the=
n the remainder is 0.</li>
</ul>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading eplus-wrapper" id=3D"8-learn-about-remainder-=
with-an-activity">Learn About Remainder with an Activity</h2>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Long division is a method that allows us to divi=
de large numbers into multiple smaller groups or parts. When we divide a di=
vidend with a divisor, the quotient obtained is the number of groups that c=
an be made, and the remainder identifies how many elements or numbers that =
will be left ungrouped.&nbsp;</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Let=E2=80=99s do a fun activity and understand b=
oth division and remainder concepts.</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Consider a group of objects that needs to be div=
ided into equal groups.&nbsp;</p>



<ul class=3D"eplus-wrapper wp-block-list">
<li class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Number of objects: Dividend</li>



<li class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Number of groups: Divisor</li>



<li class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Number of items in each small group: Quotient</=
li>



<li class=3D"eplus-wrapper">Number of items left: Remainder</li>
</ul>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper"><strong>Example 1:</strong> How can we divide 12=
 flowers among 3 children?</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full eplus-wrapper"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"620" height=3D"370" src=3D"https://www.spla=
shlearn.com/math-vocabulary/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/What-is-Remainder-4.=
png" alt=3D"zero remainder example" class=3D"wp-image-27424" title=3D"zero =
remainder example"></figure>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">When 12 flowers are divided among 3 children, ea=
ch child will get 4 flowers and no flower will be left.</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper"><strong>Example 2:</strong> Divide 9 books into =
2 equal groups. How many books are left?</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full eplus-wrapper"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"620" height=3D"370" src=3D"https://www.spla=
shlearn.com/math-vocabulary/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/What-is-Remainder-5.=
png" alt=3D"non-zero remainder example" class=3D"wp-image-27425" title=3D"n=
on-zero remainder example"></figure>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">When 9 books are divided among two groups each g=
roup gets 4 books and 1 book is left.</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">When we cannot make equal groups or distribute e=
qually to all the groups, the number that is left undivided is called the r=
emainder.&nbsp;</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading eplus-wrapper" id=3D"9-how-to-represent-the-r=
emainder">How to Represent the Remainder</h2>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">We can represent the parts of the division probl=
em using a single equation.</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper"><strong>Example 1:</strong> If you have 9 toffee=
s and you share it equally with your four friends. How many toffees will yo=
u have?&nbsp;</p>



<p class=3D"eplus-wrapper">If you give two toffees each to your friends, yo=
u would have shared 8 toffees. Only 1 toffee will remain with you, and this=
 leftover of 1 toffee is called the remainder.</p>



